{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638427"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:53:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:53:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17710"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17710"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10424"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72100"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10424"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17710"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57570"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10462"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24343"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24356"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72100"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe vestibular system plays a crucial role in maintaining balance and spatial orientation. The semicircular canals are specialised structures that detect head movements.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how semicircular canals detect angular motion of the head?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Otolith displacement within the canal","Changes in calcium concentration within the canal","Pressure changes in perilymph fluid","Direct stimulation of vestibular nerve endings","Movement of endolymph causing cupula deflection"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe semicircular canals detect angular acceleration through \u003Cstrong\u003Emovement of endolymph causing cupula deflection\u003C/strong\u003E. When the head rotates, the endolymph fluid initially lags behind due to inertia, causing displacement relative to the canal walls. This movement deflects the cupula, a gelatinous structure containing hair cells, which then triggers neural signals indicating angular motion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOtolith displacement within the canal\u003C/strong\u003E - Otoliths are found in the utricle and saccule where they detect linear acceleration, not in the semicircular canals.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanges in calcium concentration within the canal\u003C/strong\u003E - While calcium is important for hair cell function, it is not the mechanism by which angular motion is detected.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPressure changes in perilymph fluid\u003C/strong\u003E - Perilymph surrounds the membranous labyrinth but does not participate directly in motion detection.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect stimulation of vestibular nerve endings\u003C/strong\u003E - Vestibular nerve endings require activation via hair cells and are not directly stimulated by motion.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEach semicircular canal is oriented in a different plane, allowing the vestibular system to detect rotation in all three dimensions. The anterior and posterior canals are oriented vertically at right angles to each other, while the lateral canal is oriented horizontally.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Angular acceleration is detected by displacement of endolymph in the semicircular canals of the inner ear.","The cupula is deflected by endolymph movement, which bends hair cells and triggers neural signals.","Each semicircular canal is oriented to detect rotation in a specific plane."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57570"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17710"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57570"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T22:31:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T22:31:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10424"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72100"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationsh